{{World's Strongest Man Contestbox |Name =1977 World's Strongest Man |Logo =WSMLogo.jpg |Host city = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Universal Studios]], [[California]], United States |Nations participating =2 |Athletes participating =8 |Winner = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Bruce Wilhelm]] |previous = non |next = [[1978 World's Strongest Man|Hollywood 1978]] }}
The '''1977 World's Strongest Man''' was the 1st edition of [[World's Strongest Man]] and was held at the [[Universal Studios]], [[California]]<ref name="theworldsstrongestman.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.theworldsstrongestman.com/1970s_results.php |title=theworldsstrongestman.com |accessdate=2010-01-14 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100329010311/http://www.theworldsstrongestman.com/1970s_results.php |archivedate=2010-03-29 |df= }}</ref> and took place over ten weeks.<ref name=":3">{{Citation|last=HITstrongman|title=1977 World's Strongest Man|date=2014-06-07|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_OA_aqIAg1s&index=1&t=423s&list=PLUHF0SddZ9o1TE8eTPZRbut3_ZnWfJ_TD|accessdate=2017-01-14}}</ref> The title was won by [[Bruce Wilhelm]] from the United States. It was his first title. [[Bob Young (American football)|Bob Young]] from the United States finished second, and [[Ken Patera]] also from the United States third.
== Background == Originally commissioned by [[IMG (company)|Trans World International]] for [[CBS]],<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|year=2010|title=Testing for the World's Strongest Man|url=http://www.starkcenter.org/static/igh/articles/igh11.2.4.pdf|journal=Iron Game History|volume=11|pages=|via=}}</ref> the concept for the World's Strongest Man event came from Scots [[David P. Webster]] and Douglas Edmunds.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://physicalculturestudy.com/2015/04/15/1977-and-the-birth-of-the-worlds-strongest-man/|title=1977 and the birth of the World’s Strongest Man|last=Heffernan|first=Conor|date=2015-04-15|website=Physical Culture Study|access-date=2017-01-13}}</ref> Webster had earned himself a name as an event organiser through his involvement with the [[Highland games]], while Edmunds had experience in professional [[shot put]], [[Discus throw|discus]], and [[Caber toss|caber tossing]]. The event was mostly developed for entertainment purposes.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://barbend.com/1977-worlds-strongest-man-greatest-thing-since-sliced-spam/|title=The 1977 World's Strongest Man Is the Greatest Thing Since Sliced SPAM - BarBend|last=Siem|first=Brooke|date=2016-07-06|newspaper=BarBend|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-13}}</ref>
With no precedent for a worldwide 'Strongman' competition, the concept of a strongman competitor and event was new, and as such, the competitors came from a wide range of existing disciplines, including American football, powerlifting and track and field.<ref name=":0" /> This meant that none of the competitors had ever trained for the events taking place during the competition.<ref name=":1" />
In addition, several of the events in which the athletes competed were poorly thought out or dangerous, as evidenced when [[Italians|Italian]] [[Franco Columbu]] fell during the penultimate event, the Fridge Race, dislocating his knee, forcing him to retire and putting him out of action for three years.<ref name=":2">{{Cite news|url=http://www.theworldsstrongestman.com/the-worlds-strongest-man-classics-franco-columbus-tragic-fridge-race/|title=The Worlds Strongest Man Classics 1977 - Franco Columbu's tragic fridge race|date=2015-06-02|newspaper=World's Strongest Man|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-13}}</ref> The fridge carry was not reintroduced to the competition until 2004, with a crossbar added to stabilise two fridges on either side of the athlete.<ref name=":2" />
== Qualification == Qualification to the event was by invite only 'on the recommendation of experts.'<ref name=":3" />
