{{Infobox National Olympic Committee | title = Mongolian National Olympic Committee | logo = Mongolian National Olympic Committee logo.svg | size = 150px | country = Mongolia | code = MGL | created = 1956 | recognized = 1962 | association = OCA | headquarters = [[Ulaanbaatar]], [[Mongolia]] | president = [[Demchigjav Zagdsuren]] | secretary general = [[Enkhbatyn Badar-Uugan]] | website = [http://www.olympic.mn/ www.olympic.mn] }} '''Mongolian National Olympic Committee''' ({{lang-mn|Монголын Үндэсний олимпийн хороо}}) is the [[National Olympic Committee]] representing [[Mongolia]].
==History== The Mongolian National Olympic Committee was established on 2 February 26, 1956 and sanctioned by the MPRP Central Committee and the Council of Minister of the [[People's Republic of Mongolia|People's Republic]] of 2-joint 42/37 on April 26, 1956. It has since become an independent non-government organization in order to comply with the [[International Olympic Committee|International Olympic Games]] Charter and Rules.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olympic.mn/ | publisher= National Olympic Committee of Mongolia |title=Story}}</ref>
Initially, national sports associations were established to promote development and participation by youth and adults. These then evolved to focus on participation in international sports. Mongolian athletes have been involved in regular games in Asia since 1972 and have participated in 13 [[Winter Olympic Games]] and 12 [[Summer Olympic Games]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olympic.mn/ | publisher= National Olympic Committee of Mongolia |title=Leaflet}}</ref>
==Library==
The library contains books, magazine, and texts from ancient to modern times. Topics covered range from scientific reports, to sport and athlete histories. Over 10-thousand publications compose a rich library. As well, the Rings Newspaper is kept stocked.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olympic.mn/ | publisher= National Olympic Committee of Mongolia |title=Library}}</ref>
